International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
See Also
Cholera, diarrhea & dysentery update: Sep 2001 20010928.2370
In this issue:
[1 Outbreak of cholera in Mozambique
[2 Outbreak of cholera in northern Nigeria
[3 Outbreak of cholera in northern Nigeria reported expanding
[4 Outbreak of diarrheal disease in central Somalia
*****
[1
Date: Sat, 17 Nov 2001 11:28:47
From: Pablo Nart <pnart@hotmail.com>
Source: BBC news 16 November 2001

An outbreak of cholera in Mozambique has killed 60 people since August and
now spread to the capital, Maputo. The state-run Noticias newspaper said
the disease now affected more than half the country, with 2500 cases
reported. Correspondents say there are fears the disease will spread
rapidly in Maputo, particularly with the rainy season starting.
*****
[2
Date: 12 Nov 2001
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Xinhua News Agency [edited
At Least 8 Die of Cholera in Northern Nigeria
---------------------------------------------
The Nigerian health authorities Monday announced that at least 8 people
have died of cholera while 220 others have been rushed to hospital
following an outbreak of the dreadful epidemic in Nigeria's northern Kano
State.
Earlier last month, a cholera outbreak killed at least 40 people in central
Kwara State, while scores of others were hospitalized.
*****
[3
Date: Mon, 19 Nov 2001 16:54:24 -0000
From: Pablo Nart <p.nart@virgin.net>
Source: Allafrica com, 18 Nov 2001 [edited
<http://allafrica.com/stories/200111180034.html>

Barely one month after the sectarian crisis in Kano, the town is now
experiencing serious cholera outbreak, in which about 100 persons were
reportedly killed.
A source at the state's infectious diseases hospital Kano told the News
Agency of Nigeria (NAN) in Kano on Thursday, that the disease, which was
first noticed 2 weeks ago in the metropolitan [area, became pronounced
this week as it started to spread outside the capital.
The source said that a number of deaths were recorded, while 650 cases of
the epidemic were so far treated at the hospital.
The state's commissioner for health, Dr. Mansur Kabir, who confirmed
admission of 240 patients of the disease, however, said only eight persons
died as a result of the epidemic.
He said that the sanitary unit of the state ministry of health had
commenced a house to house health counselling in the metropolis.

*****
[4
Date: 14 Nov 2001
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Xinhua News Agency [edited

30 People Die From Diarrhea in Central Somalia
----------------------------------------------
About 30 people have died from diarrhea while more than 100 others are in
critical conditions in Somalia's central Galgudud region.
Health workers from Harardhereh district hospital in the region have been
carrying some anti-dehydration solutions and giving some antibiotics to the
patients, according to the local authorities.
